<v ->Okay.</v>

108
00:04:37.065 --> 00:04:39.731
Well Cleve Backster isn’t a scientist.

109
00:04:39.733 --> 00:04:44.470
He’s the country’s leading lie detector expert,

110
00:04:44.471 --> 00:04:48.406
and he got involved purely by accident.

111
00:04:48.408 --> 00:04:50.876
He was sitting in his office one night, bored,

112
00:04:50.878 --> 00:04:54.013
and he looked over at one of his plants,

113
00:04:54.015 --> 00:04:56.115
it was a dracaena, cane plant,

114
00:04:56.116 --> 00:04:57.250
and he thought to himself,

115
00:04:57.251 --> 00:04:59.251
‘I wonder what would happen if I hooked it up

116
00:04:59.253 --> 00:05:02.321
‘to one of my polygraph machines.’

117
00:05:02.323 --> 00:05:04.990
So he did, and at the time, this is in the 1960’s,

118
00:05:04.991 --> 00:05:08.060
polygraph equipment consisted of a set of electrodes

119
00:05:08.061 --> 00:05:11.363
attached to a readout mechanism that

120
00:05:11.365 --> 00:05:15.268
is like a pen describing a sideways “S.”

121
00:05:15.270 --> 00:05:17.470
And if you’re telling the truth it’s a small “s,”

122
00:05:17.471 --> 00:05:19.605
if you’re lying it’s a great, big “S.”

123
00:05:19.606 --> 00:05:23.743
So he attached his plant to this piece of equipment

124
00:05:23.745 --> 00:05:26.913
and he thought to himself, ‘Well, let’s see what happens

125
00:05:26.915 --> 00:05:28.413
‘when I pour some water in.’

126
00:05:28.415 --> 00:05:30.983
So he did, and the plant acted as though it were

127
00:05:30.985 --> 00:05:32.351
bored, you know?

128
00:05:32.353 --> 00:05:33.486
If the plant was a human being

129
00:05:33.488 --> 00:05:34.953
it would be sort of saying to itself,

130
00:05:34.955 --> 00:05:36.555
“Ho hum, ho hum.”

131
00:05:36.556 --> 00:05:38.423
So he thought to himself again,

132
00:05:38.425 --> 00:05:39.758
‘Well maybe I have to do something

133
00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:41.693
‘a little bit more drastic.

134
00:05:41.695 --> 00:05:43.863
‘Maybe I’ll burn its leaf.

135
00:05:43.865 --> 00:05:45.565
<v Regina>(laughs) That’s so cruel!</v>

136
00:05:45.566 --> 00:05:47.066
<v ->I know, absolutely!</v>

137
00:05:47.068 --> 00:05:49.335
And at the very moment he thought that,

138
00:05:49.336 --> 00:05:51.136
the plant went wild!

139
00:05:51.138 --> 00:05:54.640
The readout mechanism started describing this giant “S”

140
00:05:54.641 --> 00:05:56.775
as though the plant were stressed!

141
00:05:56.776 --> 00:05:58.545
And he kept thinking the thought,

142
00:05:58.546 --> 00:06:00.045
he went and he got some matches,

143
00:06:00.046 --> 00:06:02.981
he lit the matches, and the plant was going crazy.

144
00:06:02.983 --> 00:06:05.985
So he finally stopped thinking this,

145
00:06:05.986 --> 00:06:08.486
and the plant also calmed down

146
00:06:08.488 --> 00:06:11.891
and the “s” became smaller.

147
00:06:11.893 --> 00:06:14.093
So he thought to himself at that point,

148
00:06:14.095 --> 00:06:16.261
‘What was that?

149
00:06:16.263 --> 00:06:19.431
‘This plant has just read my thoughts!’

150
00:06:19.433 --> 00:06:22.201
So for the next 40 years Cleve Backster

151
00:06:22.203 --> 00:06:26.571
went about trying to figure out what he had just witnessed.

152
00:06:26.573 --> 00:06:29.808
He set up all kinds of experiments, not only with plants,

153
00:06:29.810 --> 00:06:32.578
but with eggs, and yogurt, and bacteria,

154
00:06:32.580 --> 00:06:34.213
even human sperm,

155
00:06:34.215 --> 00:06:35.848
just testing what he thought

156
00:06:35.850 --> 00:06:39.085
to call “primary perception,” which was

157
00:06:39.086 --> 00:06:41.486
the ability of other living things

158
00:06:41.488 --> 00:06:44.090
to pick up and read the thoughts around them,

159
00:06:44.091 --> 00:06:48.026
and this kind of transmission and reception

160
00:06:48.028 --> 00:06:51.396
that’s going on all the time between living things.

161
00:06:51.398 --> 00:06:54.833
He had some amazing results.

162
00:06:54.835 --> 00:06:57.836
He had an automated system

163
00:06:57.838 --> 00:07:01.941
whereby he had a little batch of brine shrimp

164
00:07:01.943 --> 00:07:04.310
and at a certain point when he flipped a switch

165
00:07:04.311 --> 00:07:07.946
the brine shrimp would go into some boiling water

166
00:07:07.948 --> 00:07:11.083
and die, and at that moment his plants, who were

167
00:07:11.085 --> 00:07:14.420
hooked up to polygraph machines, would all register

168
00:07:14.421 --> 00:07:19.421
alarm, and Backster, who was a great fan of Star Wars...

169
00:07:20.060 --> 00:07:23.228
Used to say, “It was like Yoda, when Yoda says,

170
00:07:23.230 --> 00:07:25.096
“ ‘I feel a disturbance in the Force.’ “

171
00:07:25.098 --> 00:07:28.000
It was like they had felt some kind of disturbance

172
00:07:28.001 --> 00:07:29.735
in the field.

173
00:07:29.736 --> 00:07:31.303
<v Regina>And another part you wrote about,</v>

174
00:07:31.305 --> 00:07:34.340
within his work, which was interesting, was

175
00:07:34.341 --> 00:07:36.341
the plants had even come to a point

176
00:07:36.343 --> 00:07:38.210
where they could discern whether or not he was

177
00:07:38.211 --> 00:07:41.613
serious in his threats as to harming them, and

178
00:07:41.615 --> 00:07:43.215
I thought that was very intriguing.

179
00:07:43.216 --> 00:07:47.286
<v ->Very, very unsettling too, because</v>

180
00:07:47.288 --> 00:07:50.456
he was working one day with a famous remote viewer,

181
00:07:50.458 --> 00:07:53.458
Ingo Swann, and Swann wanted to replicate

182
00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:55.995
what Backster had done, so he also thought

183
00:07:55.996 --> 00:07:59.365
about burning the leaf of the plant

184
00:07:59.366 --> 00:08:01.600
and the plant initially registered alarm

185
00:08:01.601 --> 00:08:03.301
on the polygraph machine,

186
00:08:03.303 --> 00:08:06.405
and then it stopped.

187
00:08:06.406 --> 00:08:10.141
And Backster and Swann looked at each other

188
00:08:10.143 --> 00:08:11.876
and said, “What was that?

189
00:08:11.878 --> 00:08:14.113
“Is this a plant learning curve?

190
00:08:14.115 --> 00:08:17.250
“The plant actually knows I’m not being serious

191
00:08:17.251 --> 00:08:19.185
“so it stopped being upset.”

192
00:08:19.186 --> 00:08:22.221
And that also was more evidence

193
00:08:22.223 --> 00:08:24.656
of this two-way flow of information,

194
00:08:24.658 --> 00:08:27.493
and that the plant has some kind of

195
00:08:27.495 --> 00:08:29.695
basic consciousness.

196
00:08:29.696 --> 00:08:33.666
So at the time, I mean no one took Backster seriously,

197
00:08:33.668 --> 00:08:37.169
because as I say he wasn’t a scientist, and it was

198
00:08:37.171 --> 00:08:38.602
many, many years ago,

199
00:08:38.605 --> 00:08:42.075
but subsequently scientists like German physicist

200
00:08:42.076 --> 00:08:44.343
Fritz Albert Popp have discovered that

201
00:08:44.345 --> 00:08:48.546
all living things are emitting tiny, tiny currents of light,

202
00:08:48.548 --> 00:08:51.883
and those currents of light are being picked up

203
00:08:51.885 --> 00:08:55.153
by other living things, and in a sense replied to.

204
00:08:55.155 --> 00:08:58.891
So Backster intuitively understood this,

205
00:08:58.893 --> 00:09:03.893
and had demonstrated it in these kind of crude experiments,

206
00:09:04.731 --> 00:09:08.600
but it took someone like Popp to show that Backster

207
00:09:08.601 --> 00:09:10.201
had been right all along.

208
00:09:10.203 --> 00:09:12.338
And he showed it through this mechanism.

209
00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:14.806
<v Regina>Right, and he’s popping up a lot.</v>

210
00:09:14.808 --> 00:09:18.143
The work of Fritz Albert Popp is coming up a lot

